<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-28T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-28T22:00:00-05:00" n="528" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d528">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/2345: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-29T12:00:00+09:00">December 29,
                                1937—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 29—2:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>696. Following has been sent to Shanghai: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“December 29, noon. Hankow’s 102, December 23, 1 p.m.<note n="66" xml:id="d528fn66">Not printed.</note> The Foreign Office
                                    states that the Navy Department has issued to forces in China
                                    instructions with regard to the second special train leaving
                                    Hankow December 30, 9 a.m. for Canton.<note n="67" xml:id="d528fn67">This train left as scheduled carrying 300
                                        foreigners including 167 Americans.</note> Please rush relay
                                    to Hankow.</p>
                                <p>Repeated to the Department.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>